          "body": "The pivot of the entire chapter is two verses. After six verses of Assyrian propaganda (vv. 13-19), verse 20 records one act: 'King Hezekiah and Isaiah the prophet, the son of Amoz, prayed about this and cried out to heaven.' Verse 21 records the response: a single angel annihilated every mighty warrior, commander, and officer in the Assyrian camp. The narrative economy is deliberate and theologically pointed. Sennacherib needed letters (v. 17), servants (v. 9), loud voices (v. 18), and a detailed rhetorical strategy to threaten Jerusalem. The LORD needed one angel. The 2 Kings 19 parallel and Isaiah 37 identify the historical backdrop: 185,000 Assyrian soldiers destroyed overnight. The Chronicler's compressed account intensifies the disproportion. Chuck Swindoll observes that the grandest moments of divine intervention in Scripture are often preceded by the quietest acts of human prayer — and the Chronicler demonstrates this with precision. The joint prayer of king and prophet models what 2 Chr. 7:14 prescribes: humble prayer reaching heaven. The parallel account in Isaiah 37:14-20 shows Hezekiah physically spreading Sennacherib's letter before the LORD — every element of Assyrian boasting laid before the God who is actually sovereign over Assyria."
